rfect_number_Cuisenaire_rods_6_exact.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"2=
50" height=3D"197" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"437" data-f=
ile-height=3D"345"></a><figcaption>Illustration of the perfect number statu=
s of the number 6</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=3D"Numb=
er theory">number theory</a>, a <b>perfect number</b> is a <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positive_integer" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"P=
ositive integer">positive integer</a> that is equal to the sum of its posit=
ive proper <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Divisor" title=3D"Divis=
or">divisors</a>, that is, divisors excluding the number itself.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pe=
rfect_number#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For instance, 6 has proper divisors 1,=
 2, and 3, and 1 + 2 + 3 =3D 6, so 6 is a perfect number. The next perfect =
number is 28, because 1 + 2 + 4 + 7 + 14 =3D 28.
</p><p>The first seven perfect numbers are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/6_(number)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"6 (number)">6</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/28_(number)" title=3D"28 (number)">28<=
/a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/496_(number)" title=3D"496 (n=
umber)">496</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/8128_(number)" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"8128 (number)">8128</a>, 33550336, 8589869056,=
 and 137438691328.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_number#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The sum of proper divisors of a number is called its <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aliquot_sum" title=3D"Aliquot sum">aliquot sum</a=
>, so a perfect number is one that is equal to its aliquot sum. Equivalentl=
y, a perfect number is a number that is half the sum of all of its positive=
 divisors; in symbols, <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inl=
ine"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"d=
isplay: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=
=3D"{\displaystyle \sigma _{1}(n)=3D2n}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
