<p>In about 300&nbsp;BC Euclid showed that if 2<sup><i>p</i></sup>&nbsp;=E2=
=88=92&nbsp;1 is prime then 2<sup><i>p</i>=E2=88=921</sup>(2<sup><i>p</i></=
sup>&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;1) is perfect.
The first four perfect numbers were the only ones known to early <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greek_mathematics" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Greek mathematics">Greek mathematics</a>, and the mathematician <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicomachus" title=3D"Nicomachus">Nicoma=
chus</a> noted 8128 as early as around AD&nbsp;100.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dick=
inson_LE_(1919)_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Perfect_number#cite_note-Dickinson_LE_(1919)-4"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In modern=
 language, Nicomachus states without proof that <em>every</em> perfect numb=
er is of the form <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline">=
<span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"displa=
y: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
