<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Odd_perfect_numbers">Odd pe=
rfect numbers</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DPerfect_number&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Odd perfect numbers"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1287834656">
<div role=3D"note" aria-labelledby=3D"unsolved-label-mathematics" class=3D"=
unsolved">
<div><span class=3D"unsolved-label" id=3D"unsolved-label-mathematics">Unsol=
ved problem in mathematics</span></div>
<div class=3D"unsolved-body">Are there any odd perfect numbers?</div>
<div class=3D"unsolved-more"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_=
of_unsolved_problems_in_mathematics" title=3D"List of unsolved problems in =
mathematics">More unsolved problems in mathematics</a></div>
</div>
<p>It is unknown whether any odd perfect numbers exist, though various resu=
lts have been obtained. In 1496, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J=
acques_Lef%C3%A8vre_d%27%C3%89taples" title=3D"Jacques Lef=C3=A8vre d'=C3=
=89taples">Jacques Lef=C3=A8vre</a> stated that Euclid's rule gives all per=
fect numbers,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_number#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> thus implyi=
ng that no odd perfect number exists, but Euler himself stated: "Whether&nb=
sp;... there are any odd perfect numbers is a most difficult question".<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Perfect_number#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> More recently, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Pomerance" title=3D"Carl Pomerance">Carl P=
omerance</a> has presented a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heuri=
stic_argument" title=3D"Heuristic argument">heuristic argument</a> suggesti=
ng that indeed no odd perfect number should exist.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-oddpe=
rfect_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pe=
rfect_number#cite_note-oddperfect-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> All perfect numbers are a=
lso <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harmonic_divisor_number" title=
=3D"Harmonic divisor number">harmonic divisor numbers</a>, and it has been =
conjectured as well that there are no odd harmonic divisor numbers other th=
an 1.
</p><p>Any odd perfect number <i>N</i> must satisfy the following condition=
s:
</p>
<ul><li><i>N</i> &gt; 10<sup>1500</sup>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ochem_and_Rao_(=
2012)_22-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pe=
rfect_number#cite_note-Ochem_and_Rao_(2012)-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><i>N</i> is not divisible by 105.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-K=C3=BChnel_U_23-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_numb=
er#cite_note-K%C3%BChnel_U-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><i>N</i> is of the form <i>N</i> =E2=89=A1 1 (mod 12) or <i>N</i> =E2=
=89=A1 117 (mod 468) or <i>N</i> =E2=89=A1 81 (mod 324).<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-Roberts_T_(2008)_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Perfect_number#cite_note-Roberts_T_(2008)-24"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>The largest <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_power" title=
=3D"Prime power">prime power</a> <i>p<sup>a</sup></i> that divides <i>N</i>=
 is greater than 10<sup>62</sup>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ochem_and_Rao_(2012)_2=
2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_n=
umber#cite_note-Ochem_and_Rao_(2012)-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>The largest prime factor of <i>N</i> is greater than 10<sup>8</sup>,<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Goto_and_Ohno_(2008)_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_number#cite_note-Goto_and_Ohno_(2008)=
-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> and less than <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-ele=
ment-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" st=
yle=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" a=
lttext=3D"{\displaystyle {\sqrt[{3}]{3N}}.}">
