an></div>
<p>All even perfect numbers have a very precise form; odd perfect numbers e=
ither do not exist or are rare. There are a number of results on perfect nu=
mbers that are actually quite easy to prove but nevertheless superficially =
impressive; some of them also come under <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Richard_K._Guy" title=3D"Richard K. Guy">Richard Guy</a>'s <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strong_law_of_small_numbers" title=3D"Str=
ong law of small numbers">strong law of small numbers</a>:
</p>
<ul><li>The only even perfect number of the form <i>n</i><sup>3</sup>&nbsp;=
+&nbsp;1 is 28 (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_number#CIT=
EREFMakowski1962">Makowski 1962</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_number#cite_note-51"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup></li>
<li>28 is also the only even perfect number that is a sum of two positive c=
ubes of integers (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_number#C=
ITEREFGallardo2010">Gallardo 2010</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_number#cite_note-5=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup></li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplicative_inverse" ti=
tle=3D"Multiplicative inverse">reciprocals</a> of the divisors of a perfect=
