<p>The sum of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proper_divisor" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Proper divisor">proper divisors</a> gives variou=
s other kinds of numbers. Numbers where the sum is less than the number its=
elf are called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deficient_number" t=
itle=3D"Deficient number">deficient</a>, and where it is greater than the n=
umber, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abundant_number" title=3D"A=
bundant number">abundant</a>. These terms, together with <i>perfect</i> its=
elf, come from Greek <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerology" t=
itle=3D"Numerology">numerology</a>. A pair of numbers which are the sum of =
each other's proper divisors are called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Amicable_number" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Amicable number">amic=
able</a>, and larger cycles of numbers are called <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Sociable_number" title=3D"Sociable number">sociable</a>. A =
positive integer such that every smaller positive integer is a sum of disti=
nct divisors of it is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Practical_=
number" title=3D"Practical number">practical number</a>.
</p><p>By definition, a perfect number is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Fixed_point_(mathematics)" title=3D"Fixed point (mathematics)">fi=
xed point</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Restricted_di=
visor_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Restricted divisor function"=
>restricted divisor function</a> <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>s</i>(<i>n</i>) =
=3D <i>=CF=83</i>(<i>n</i>) =E2=88=92 <i>n</i></span>, and the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aliquot_sequence" title=3D"Aliquot sequence">a=
liquot sequence</a> associated with a perfect number is a constant sequence=
.  All perfect numbers are also <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-el=
ement-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" s=
tyle=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" =
alttext=3D"{\displaystyle {\mathcal {S}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
